# DPPchain Specification v0.1 — Simple Producer Format

**We stand for free, unmanipulated data.**

*This document defines DPPchain's open format for small producers. For architecture see SPEC.md. For examples see SPEC2.md. For technical standards see SPEC3.md.*

---

## The problem this solves

UNTP and GS1 are the right standards for large manufacturers. They are already embedded in SAP, Oracle, and enterprise ERP systems. Large companies will implement DPP through their IT departments and consultants.

A small farmer, a seamstress, a sawmill, a dairy, a market gardener — they do not have an IT department. They do not have a compliance budget. They do not understand JSON-LD. They are frightened of another regulatory requirement that will cost them money they do not have.

At the same time, the consumer wants to know if the cotton is Polish or Chinese. If the milk is local or reconstituted. If the timber is legal. If the vegetables are what they claim to be.

These two groups are cut off from each other. The small producer has a true product story but no tool to tell it in a format the system understands. The consumer wants the truth but gets marketing.

DPPchain's simple producer format bridges this gap.

---

## Design principles

**No software required**
A producer can create a valid DPP record using a web form, a mobile app, or even a structured text file. No ERP. No IT department. No consultant.

**No licence fee**
The format is open. Free forever. No subscription. No per-product fee.

**No technical knowledge required**
The producer answers plain language questions. The system generates the structured record. They never see JSON-LD unless they want to.

**Interoperable by design**
Records created in the simple format are automatically translatable to UNTP. A small producer who starts simple can migrate to full UNTP compliance without losing any data. The simple format is a subset, not a fork.

**Inheritance built in**
If a supplier already has a DPP — in any format — the producer references it by identifier. The system handles the rest. The producer does not re-verify what their supplier already verified.

