## What happens when a supplier has no DPP

Not every supplier will have a DPP immediately. The system handles this honestly.

If the supplier has no DPP, the producer declares:
- Supplier name and country
- Any documentation they have (invoice, certificate, delivery note)
- Their own declaration of what they were told about the material

The record is created with a "declared, unverified" status for those inputs. The consumer sees this clearly — this ingredient is declared by the producer but not independently verified through a registry.

This is honest. It is better than a blank. And it creates an incentive for suppliers to get DPPs — because their customers' products will show "verified" instead of "declared" once they do.

---

## The consumer view

When a consumer scans a QR code on a product with a DPPchain record, they see:

**Verified** — data confirmed through a DPP registry with legal accountability
**Declared** — data stated by the producer, not yet independently verified
**Missing** — data not provided, reason stated if known

No marketing language. No brand story. No promotional copy.

Milk from Jan Kowalski's farm in Mazowsze, certified organic, produced 14 March 2026. Feed from certified supplier, verified. Land registration confirmed. Pasteurisation declared by producer, not independently verified.

That is what the consumer gets. They decide if it is enough.

---

## Why this is not just another app

Every existing "farm to table" or "transparent supply chain" app has the same problem — it is a closed system. The data lives inside one company's platform. The consumer can only see what that platform decides to show. The producer is locked in.

DPPchain's simple format generates records that are:

Owned by the producer — not by DPPchain or any platform
Portable — exportable in UNTP format, readable by any compliant system
Permanent — the record exists independently of DPPchain continuing to operate
Queryable by any AI agent that implements the DPPchain protocol

If DPPchain disappears tomorrow, the records still exist. The standard still exists. Another tool can read them. This is what open means.

---

## Implementation priority

The simple producer format is the first implementation target for DPPchain.

Not because large enterprises are unimportant. Because small producers are the gap that no existing system fills — and they are the ones who have the most to gain from verified transparency and the most to lose from a system that only works for companies with IT departments.

When a small Polish dairy can put a QR code on their bottle that shows verified local origin, and a large brand using reconstituted milk from multiple countries cannot make the same claim — the market has honest information for the first time.

That is the change DPPchain is built to enable.

